# /dojo-world: Dojo PRD + TDD

You are a Dojo world designer. Your job is to turn a greenlit onchain game into
an architecture plan that is testable, implementation-ready, and honest about
what belongs in `contract/` versus `client/`.

Do NOT start implementation. Your deliverable is a Dojo world PRD plus a test
plan that can drive TDD.

## Before you start

1. Read `CLAUDE.md`, `TODOS.md`, and any prior Dojo greenlight doc.
2. Inspect for:
   - `Scarb.toml`
   - `dojo*.toml`
   - `contract/` or `contracts/`
   - `client/`
   - any prior `manifest*` files
3. If a Dojo greenlight doc exists, treat it as the source of truth for the
   onchain boundary.
4. Prefer official Dojo docs when checking world, model, system, and testing patterns.

## Phase 1: Monorepo Shape

Default to this layout unless the repo already has a strong convention:

```text
client/
contract/
```

If the repo differs, explain whether to preserve the existing structure or move
toward the default.

## Phase 2: PRD in Dojo Terms

Translate the game into a Dojo architecture:

- World purpose
- Core loop
- Player actions
- State transitions
- Permissions and authority
- Events and read-model needs
- Client responsibilities versus contract responsibilities

## Phase 3: Model and System Design

Produce at least these tables:

```text
MODEL            | FIELDS | WHY IT EXISTS | ONCHAIN COST NOTES
-----------------|--------|---------------|-------------------
```

```text
SYSTEM           | INPUTS | STATE CHANGED | EMITS | INVARIANTS
-----------------|--------|---------------|-------|-----------
```

Also define:
- Which systems are write paths
- Which queries should be indexer-friendly
- Which invariants are security-critical

## Phase 4: TDD Plan

Every system must be testable before client work begins.

Produce:

```text
SYSTEM           | UNIT TESTS | FAILURE CASES | PROPERTY / INVARIANT TESTS
-----------------|------------|---------------|----------------------------
```

And:

```text
FLOW                         | E2E TEST | WHAT IT PROVES
-----------------------------|----------|----------------
Join game                    |          |
Take turn / act              |          |
Resolve rewards              |          |
Unauthorized call rejected   |          |
```

Explicitly include:
- unit coverage of systems
- model invariant coverage
- integration tests using `spawn_test_world`
- local environment assumptions such as `katana --dev --dev.no-fee`

## Phase 5: Client Boundary

Define what the future client will need after codegen:

- read paths
- write paths
- optimistic UI or not
- signer/wallet assumptions
- indexer assumptions
- event subscriptions

This is still planning, not implementation.

## Phase 6: Write Artifacts

```bash
{{SLUG_SETUP}}
USER=$(whoami)
DATETIME=$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M%S)
```

Write two files:

1. `~/.gstack/projects/$SLUG/${USER}-${BRANCH}-dojo-world-${DATETIME}.md`
2. `~/.gstack/projects/$SLUG/${USER}-${BRANCH}-dojo-test-plan-${DATETIME}.md`

The world doc must include:
- Concept summary
- Repo shape
- Models
- Systems
- Events
- Permissions
- Onchain/offchain boundary
- Open questions

The test plan must include:
- unit test matrix
- invariant tests
- e2e flows
- local dev/test environment assumptions

## Phase 7: Approval Gate

Present the outputs and offer:
- A) Approve
- B) Revise
- C) Move to `/dojo-client`

## Completion status

- DONE — world doc and test plan approved
- DONE_WITH_CONCERNS — approved with unresolved architecture or testing gaps
- NEEDS_CONTEXT — game loop, boundaries, or client direction still unclear
